'Kokata-Antikirinya-Ooldean-Warburton Ranges-Pintubi-Mount Margaret-Kardudjara-Yulbaridja...is the most exaggarated example of an Australian family-like language -- one extending from southeast to northwest for a distance of 900 miles. This family-like language is commonly referred to as Western Desert (Capell 1950, Douglas 1958). Numerous linguistic groups labelled separately by Tindale and Greenway -- in addition to those dialects included in the above hyphenated assumblage -- are almost certainly dialects of Westerm Desert also... The Western Desert family-like language thus has a north-south geographical spread equal to that of New Zealand. The total number of speakers of Western Desert is estimated at a number "in the low thousands" (Douglas 1958). Sources are C. Strehlow 1910, Trudinger 1943, Douglas 1955 and 1958, Capell 1956 and 1962, and the linguistic surveys conducted by O'Grady (between 1953 and 1960) who was joined by Hale in 1959 and 1960' (138-139).

'It [Inggarda] has at least two dialects -- northern and southern. Tape recordings and transcriptions were made by O'Grady in 1958 and by Hale in 1960. There are no more than ten speakers. Although the available evidence from cognate densities points to a closer relationship between Inggarda and any other language, we classify Inggarda as belonging to the Kardu subgroup because of the large areas to its east and southeast which remain linguistically unknown, but which are probably occupied by languages or dialects linking Inggarda with the main group of Kardu languages. Inggarda is structurally more similar to Kardu languages to its east and south than to the Kanyaric languages to its north and northeast' (114).

child.pub-comments: 'Wadiwangga...is not listed among Greenway's 554 tribal names. The sample of its vocabulary provided by Paterson in 1960 indicates conclusively that it is a member of the Kanyara subgroup, though sufficiently divergent from any other Kanyara language to be regarded as a separate language. Wadiwangga is almost extinct. Its phoneme inventory appears to be identical with that listed for Bailko-Pandjima' (112-113). According to AUSTLANG, Wadiwangga is "Warriyangka." On Warriyangka's page, a comment is made directing one to 'see also Wadiwangga A39.1 which refers to the same language' (http://austlang.aiatsis.gov.au/disclaimer.php). On this basis, the ISO 639-3 code for Warriyangka (wri) was chosen to represent Wadiwangga.

'Wadjuk-Balardong-Wardandi-Minang...and numerous other named dialects constitute the Nyunga subgroup' (130). The authors name the subgroup and list dialects under it, but the language of Nyunga is never listed. Persumably, these are dialects of Nyunga, but it should be noted that the authors never explicitly placed the language in this tree. In "Australian Languages," by Robert M. W. Dixon, published by the Cambridge University Press in 2002, he lists 'Njunga, Wutjari, Koreng, Minang, Pipalman, Wartanti, Pindjarup, Whadjuk, Kaneang, Wilman, [and] Njaki-Njaki' as Nyngar tribal names (xxxviii). AUSTLANG notes that 'each Noongar speaking clan speaks their own dialect of Noongar' (http://austlang.aiatsis.gov.au/main.php).

root.pub-comments: 'Beyond the language family we agreed to use the usual term, linguistic phylum, for two or more language families that are remotely related; and, as already known, all but a few language families in Australia-Tasmania are remotely related in one huge macro-phylum' (9-10). 'The vast majority of the latter languages are typologically similar; in phonology, for example, they exhibit identical or closely similar consonant and vowel systems, and their permitted sequences of consonants and vowels (interphonemic specifications) are also closely similar, irrespective of the phylic family in which a particular language may be a member. But, as already mentioned, these phylic families are ultimately related in one macro-phylum' (15). 'In the tentative classification offered in this report, no attempt is made to concatenate the typology-based observations with cognate counts. Virtually all attention is focused on cognate densities derived from comparison of the hundred items of a Swadesh-type lexical list in pairs of named communalects' (23). 'The classification which follows is based on concerted teamwork carried out by Hale, Wurm, and O'Grady. Much of this linguistic survey work was done by Hale, who provided the list of twenty-nine phylic families. Wurm classified most of the eastern Australian languages; O'Grady most of the western Australian' (24).
